Design Review
The design describes a 6-step AI initiative management platform. It's essentially a full-stack web application with:

A structured data store (AI Case Library)
A submission portal (CRUD forms)
A browsable/filterable UI
An analytics dashboard with charts
A ranking/leaderboard engine
An AI-powered solution design agent (semantic search + generation)
It's ambitious but well-scoped. Each step builds on the previous one, which is good for incremental delivery.

Detailed Development Plan
Phase 1: Project Foundation & Data Layer
Tech stack recommendation: Python (FastAPI backend) + React frontend + SQLite (or DynamoDB if you want AWS-native). This keeps it hackathon-friendly.

What I'd build:

FastAPI project scaffold with CORS, error handling
SQLAlchemy models for the Case Library schema (Case ID, Owner Login, Job Level, Program/Team, Use Case Title, Problem Statement, AI Technique, Tools/Services, Key Prompts, Input Data, Output/Outcome, Performance Metrics, Status, Date, Rank)
Auto-generated fields: Case ID (UUID), Date (timestamp), Rank (computed)
Database migrations with Alembic
CRUD API endpoints: POST /cases, GET /cases, GET /cases/{id}, PUT /cases/{id}, DELETE /cases/{id}
Seed data script with sample cases
Phase 2: Learner Input Portal (Submission Form)
React form component with all case fields
Dropdown selections for categorical fields (AI Technique, Status, Job Level, Program/Team)
Validation rules: required fields, format checks
Draft/Save/Submit workflow with status field (draft, submitted, approved)
API endpoints for draft management: POST /cases/draft, PUT /cases/{id}/submit
Phase 3: Filterable Browse UI
Data table component (using something like TanStack Table or AG Grid)
Multi-column filtering: text search, dropdown filters, date range
Sorting on every column
Pagination
CSV export endpoint: GET /cases/export?format=csv
API query params: GET /cases?program=X&technique=Y&status=Z&sort=date&order=desc
Phase 4: Analytics Dashboard
Dashboard page with chart components (Chart.js or Recharts)
Charts to build:
Bar chart: initiatives by Program/Team
Pie chart: distribution of AI techniques
Stacked bar: performance metrics (time saved, accuracy, cost reduction)
Funnel/pipeline: status progression (ideation → POC → production)
Line chart: submissions over time
Aggregation API endpoints: GET /analytics/by-program, GET /analytics/by-technique, GET /analytics/by-status, GET /analytics/trends
Drill-down: clicking a chart segment filters the browse view
Phase 5: Ranking Engine
Weighted scoring algorithm:
Impact (40%): time saved + cost reduction + accuracy gain
Scalability (25%): reusability score
Complexity vs Effort (20%): inverse of effort-to-impact ratio
Innovation (15%): novelty factor
API: GET /rankings?weights=impact:40,scalability:25,complexity:20,innovation:15
Leaderboard UI component with configurable weight sliders
Side-by-side comparison view for top initiatives
Rank auto-updates when weights change
Phase 6: AI Solution Design Agent
Embedding generation for all cases (using Amazon Bedrock or OpenAI)
Vector store for semantic search (FAISS or pgvector)
Agent endpoint: POST /agent/design
Input: problem description text
Process: embed query → find top-K similar cases → generate solution design via LLM
Output: suggested techniques, reference cases, estimated effort, implementation steps
Conversational follow-up support via session tracking
Prompt engineering for structured output
Estimated Timeline (Hackathon pace)
Phase	Effort
Phase 1: Foundation & Data	~2-3 hours
Phase 2: Input Portal	~2-3 hours
Phase 3: Browse UI	~2-3 hours
Phase 4: Analytics	~3-4 hours
Phase 5: Ranking	~2-3 hours
Phase 6: AI Agent	~4-5 hours
Total: roughly 15-21 hours of focused development.